{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492808"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1160"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1160"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.13,0.8,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112667"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1160"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1160"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94697"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12935"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30172"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46008"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112667"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 18-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of perianal pain and discharge. Over the last three months she has been experiencing intermittent bloody diarrhoea and perineal discharge. She has lost 8 kg of body weight. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and slightly tender on palpation in the left lower quadrant. Rectal examination is difficult to perform due to pain, but an area of erythematous swelling is visible close to the anal margin discharging pus, consistent with a perianal abscess. Gentle pressure to her perineum shows discharge of faeculent material. Several anal tags are also present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIleocolonoscopy shows patchy areas of severe inflammatory change with deep linear ulcerations throughout both the colon and terminal ileum, with some areas of normal appearing mucosa. There are some stenosing features in the terminal ileum. She is commenced on initial treatment for her condition with significant initial improvement, but when reviewed, her perineal signs are still present. Additionally, although her diarrhoea has improved it has not completely resolved.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most appropriate for her long-term management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tocilizumab","Rituximab","Infliximab","Natalizumab","Secukinumab"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Crohn\u0027s disease with several high-risk factors predictive of a severe disease course. These include young age at diagnosis, ileal/ileocolonic involvement, perianal disease with likely fistula formation, deep ulcerations, and a penetrating/stenosing pattern of disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfliximab\u003C/strong\u003E, a TNF-alpha inhibitor, has demonstrated superior efficacy in inducing and maintaining remission in severe Crohn\u0027s disease, particularly in patients with perianal disease. It has extensive long-term safety data and is considered first-line therapy for patients with high-risk features. The rapid onset of action and proven efficacy in healing fistulas make it particularly suitable for this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETocilizumab\u003C/strong\u003E, an IL-6 receptor antagonist, is primarily used in rheumatoid arthritis and has no established role in Crohn\u0027s disease. While IL-6 is involved in the inflammatory cascade, targeting this pathway alone has not shown significant benefits in inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERituximab\u003C/strong\u003E, a B-cell depleting agent, is not indicated for Crohn\u0027s disease and may potentially worsen disease activity. It is primarily used in conditions where B-cell dysfunction plays a central role, such as rheumatoid arthritis and certain vasculitides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENatalizumab\u003C/strong\u003E, while effective in Crohn\u0027s disease, carries a risk of progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy and requires extensive pre-treatment screening. It is also not covered under PBS for Crohn\u0027s disease, in contrast to relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecukinumab\u003C/strong\u003E, an IL-17A inhibitor, has shown a potential to worsen inflammatory bowel disease and is contraindicated in Crohn\u0027s disease. It is primarily used in conditions such as psoriasis and ankylosing spondylitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Factors in Crohn\u0027s disease predictive of a severe course include young age, extensive bowel involvement, deep ulcerations, ileal/ileocolonic involvement, perianal disease, and penetrating/stenosing behaviour.","Anti-TNF therapy is recommended as first-line treatment for Crohn\u0027s disease with high-risk features rather than a traditional step-up approach.","Infliximab has demonstrated superior efficacy in inducing and maintaining remission in severe Crohn\u0027s disease, particularly for perianal disease."],"references":["Lichtenstein GR, Lotus EV, Isaacs KL, et al. ACG Clinical Guideline: Management of Crohn\u2019s Disease in Adults. Am J Gastroenterol 2018; 113:481\u201317.","Gastroenterological Society of Australia. Cinical update for general practitioners and physicians: Inflammatory bowel sisease. Melbourne: GESA, 2018","Peyrin-Biroulet L, Sandborn WJ. Panaccione R, et al. Tumour necrosis factor inhibitors in inflammatory bowel disease: the story continues. Ther Adv Gastroenterol 2021; 14: 1\u201322","Update in inflammatory bowel disease. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2012 Nov 2;38:956\u201361. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2009/december/inflammatory-bowel-disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94697"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1160"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94697"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-03T09:21:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-03T09:21:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1160"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112667"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt